'''Otto Tellman''' (22 May 1927, [[Agnita]], [[Romania]] – 10 January 2013, [[Germany]]) was a Romanian [[handball]] player and coach. He played as a pivot.

He started playing in 1945 in his hometown, Agnita, and transferred to [[CSA Steaua București (handball)|Steaua Bucharest]] in 1949.

An 18-time national champion with Steaua, either as a player or as a coach, he was also a member of [[Romania men's national handball team|Romania's national team]] that won the [[1961 World Men's Handball Championship]] in Western Germany.<ref name="Steaua">{{cite web|url=http://www.fcsteaua.ro/index/section/articles/article/36406|title=A decedat extraordinarul handbalist Otto Tellman|language=Romanian|accessdate=April 27, 2014}}</ref><ref name="SbZ">{{cite web|url=http://www.siebenbuerger.de/zeitung/artikel/interviews/13029-handball_weltmeister-otto-tellmann-ist.html|title=Handball-Weltmeister Otto Tellmann ist tot|language=German|accessdate=April 27, 2014}}</ref>

Tellmann, who played for 18 years for Steaua, became after he retired from active play a coach, managing the Voinţa Bucharest, [[CS Dinamo Bucureşti (men's handball)|Dinamo Bucharest]] and Steaua teams, teams with which he won several national championships, the [[Spartakiad]], and twice the [[EHF Champions League]].<ref name="SbZ"/>

In 1985, he defected to Western Germany, and coached Nürnberg's women's team.<ref name="Steaua"/>

In 1986 he began coaching the men's team [[TV Bötzingen]], where he stayed until 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvboetzingen-handball.de/extrainer.html|title=Otto Tellmann (bis 2002)|language=German|accessdate=April 27, 2014}}</ref>

With [[Simon Schobel]], [[Vlado Stenzel]], [[Petre Ivănescu]] and [[Ioan Kunst-Ghermănescu]] he lectured at the Internationale Freiburger Handballschule ("International Freiburg Handball School").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chilli-freiburg.de/pdf/archiv/dezember04/polizei.pdf|title=Polizeieskorte für Welthandballer|language=German|accessdate=April 27, 2014}}</ref>

In 2009 Tellmann, who played 48 games for the national team,<ref name="SbZ"/> was awarded the Romanian Sport Merit Order, Second Class.<ref name="Steaua"/>

